var __index = {"config":{"lang":["en"],"separator":"[\\s\\-]+","pipeline":["stopWordFilter"]},"docs":[{"location":"index.html","title":"Welcome to CCA Guide","text":"<p>This is a collection of notes and resources for some courses at California Crosspoint Academy.</p> <p>Disclaimer</p> <p>This guide is not updated, endorsed, or approved by the California Crosspoint Academy. Content may be outdated or incorrect.  Please refer to the teachers for the most up-to-date information.</p> <p>This is not meant to replace taking notes and creating your own resources, but rather to supplement it.</p> <p>If you found this guide helpful, please consider starring the GitHub repository and sharing it with others.</p>"},{"location":"index.html#contributing","title":"Contributing","text":"<p>If you notice that any information is incorrect, missing, or would like content removed, open an issue.</p> <p>If you would like to make changes or add your content to the guide, fork the repository and open a pull request.</p>"},{"location":"ap-calculus-bc/take-home-quiz/quiz-1.html","title":"Take Home Quiz 1","text":""},{"location":"ap-calculus-bc/take-home-quiz/quiz-1.html#prompt","title":"Prompt","text":"<p>In the sport of basketball, when a player is \"fouled,\" they have the opportunity to take two \"free-throws,\" where the player shoots the ball two times and can give his team one point for each basket made</p> <p>An important statistic in basketball is a player's free-throw success percentage over the basketball season. For example, if a player has 10 free-throw attempts made 8 baskets, their percentage is 80%.</p> <p>Interestingly, the percentage is always rounded to the nearest percent (for the ease of the viewing public, which probably does not know math). For example, if a player has made 7 out of 22 free-throws, then the reported percentage is 32%.</p> <p>During a game, the announcer says that a player is making 78% of their free throws at the moment that the player is fouled. The player makes two free-throw attempts and makes the first one but misses the second attempt. After the statistics are updated, the player is now making 76% of their free-throws.</p> <p>For this player, what are all possible numbers of free-throws made and attempted so far this season (including the ones that were just made)? (Hint: There are a finite number of solutions)</p>"},{"location":"ap-calculus-bc/take-home-quiz/quiz-1.html#solution","title":"Solution","text":"<p>Click here to view the solution.</p>"},{"location":"ap-calculus-bc/take-home-quiz/quiz-1.html#verification","title":"Verification","text":"<p>In Kotlin, the solution can be verified by running the following code:</p> <pre><code>fun calculatePercentages(\npercentInitial: Int,\npercentFinal: Int,\nsuccesses: Int,\nrounds: Int,\niterations: Int,\n): MutableList&lt;Pair&lt;Int, Int&gt;&gt; {\nval solutions = mutableListOf&lt;Pair&lt;Int, Int&gt;&gt;();\nassert(iterations &gt; 1) { \"iterations $iterations must be greater than 1\" };\nfor (n in 1..iterations) {\nfor (s in 1..n) {\nval rawPercent = s.toDouble() / n.toDouble();\nval percentRounded = Math.round(rawPercent * 100).toInt();\nval finalSuccesses = s + successes;\nval finalRounds = n + rounds;\nval rawFinalPercent = finalSuccesses.toDouble() / finalRounds.toDouble();\nval finalPercentRounded = Math.round(rawFinalPercent * 100).toInt();\nif (percentRounded == percentInitial &amp;&amp; finalPercentRounded == percentFinal) {\nsolutions.add(Pair(s, n));\n}\n}\n}\nreturn solutions;\n}\n//sampleStart\nfun main() {\nval iterations = 1000;\ncalculatePercentages(78, 76, 1, 2, iterations).forEach {\nprintln(\"s: ${it.first}, n: ${it.second}\")\n}\n}\n//sampleEnd\n</code></pre>"},{"location":"ap-literature/assignments/analyzing-plot-structure.html","title":"Analyzing Plot Structure","text":""},{"location":"ap-literature/assignments/analyzing-plot-structure.html#prompt","title":"Prompt","text":"<p>Choose a story \u2013 novel, myth, film, short story, etc. That does not tell its story chronologically and analyze its plot. (5 elements)</p> <p>Then write a paragraph (5-7 sentences) where you answer the following questions.</p> <ul> <li>What effect does this plot choice have on the story as a whole?</li> <li>How do these structural choices impact the way we understand the characters and the surrounding setting?</li> </ul>"},{"location":"ap-literature/assignments/analyzing-plot-structure.html#response","title":"Response","text":""},{"location":"ap-literature/assignments/analyzing-plot-structure.html#plot-chart-analysis","title":"Plot Chart Analysis","text":""},{"location":"ap-literature/assignments/analyzing-plot-structure.html#exposition","title":"Exposition","text":"<p>The film introduces three timelines. There is the land timeline, where shows soldiers stranded on the beach of Dunkirk, waiting for evacuation. The \"sea\" timeline is about a civilian boat heading towards Dunkirk to assist in the evacuation. The \"air\" timeline is about a British pilot providing air cover. The different timelines set up the various arenas of conflict and create the backdrop for the drama.</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/assignments/analyzing-plot-structure.html#rising-action","title":"Rising Action","text":"<p>Each timeline has its own set of challenges - I guess you can technically say there are three mini plot structures - which all build towards on overarching structure. On the land timeline, soldiers struggle with enemy attacks and waiting for rescue. On the sea, the civilian boat faces the dangerous journey and rescues a shell-shocked soldier. In the air, the pilot engages in multiple dogfights.</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/assignments/analyzing-plot-structure.html#climax","title":"Climax","text":"<p>The timelines start converging. The civilian boat arrives at Dunkirk, some get destroyed, the air cover intensifies, and the soldiers get a glimmer of hope for evacuation. The stakes are at their highest as each timeline reaches its most critical moment.</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/assignments/analyzing-plot-structure.html#falling-action","title":"Falling Action","text":"<p>Rescues are made. However there sacrifices/consequences. The pilot is running out of fuel, the civilian boat manages to take on several soldiers, and some soldiers are finally evacuated.</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/assignments/analyzing-plot-structure.html#resolution","title":"Resolution","text":"<p>The film ends with a sense of bittersweet victory. The civilian boat returns home and are hailed as heroes; the pilot lands his plane but is captured; and the evacuated soldiers, while safe, ponder the larger war ahead.</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/assignments/analyzing-plot-structure.html#questions","title":"Questions","text":"<p>I\u2019ve chosen Dunkirk, directed by Christopher Nolan, and is known for its unique 3 consecutive timelines.</p> <p>This structure disrupts a linear, chronological sequence, which keeps the audience engaged and maintains an elevated level of suspense. Sometimes, the transitions between timelines was jarring, going from a relatively quiet scene to the middle of a dogfight. However, the broken form of narrative/plot structure created a sense of urgency and suspense - you could say that while watching the movie, I was sort of on the edge of my seat the entire time. You wouldn't necessarily be able \u201cpredict\u201d what would be the next scene and this also led to some confusion for me while watching for the first time. I guess this method of story telling could mimic some of the emotions felt by the actual soldiers that were in the movie.</p> <p>This structure of having 3 different timelines sort of lets the audience appreciate the scale of the effort at Dunkirk. Most of the time, stories will focus on one or a few specific characters (oftentimes the protagonists) throughout the plot, but by using 3 different timelines, which all are scaled differently, it allows the audience to understand the teamwork, cooperation, and luck that was on the Allies side. The movie doesn't also seem to have a specific set of protagonists either, which allows the audience to be able to make form generalized viewpoints about what went down at Dunkirk. This choice deepens the audience\u2019s understanding of the scale of human effort involved in the Dunkirk evacuation - showing that the event was not just a single mission, but a collective effort that required coordination, sacrifice, and courage from all fronts.</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/assignments/characterization-first-day.html","title":"Characterization of the First Day","text":"<ol> <li> <p>Who is the protagonist? Antagonist? How do the minor characters function in the story?</p> <p>Protagonists (mother, girl). Antagonist (people who rejected at first school). The minor characters are the core contributors to the plot of the story - they incite the conflict and resolve them.</p> </li> <li> <p>What do specific details reveal about characters\u2019 values, beliefs, assumptions, biases, and cultural norms?</p> <p>The mother does not know how to read, but is still strong-minded and decisive when it comes to sending her daughter to school.</p> <p>The daughter seems a bit lost - which is understandable as she\u2019s just in kindergarten following her mom around</p> </li> <li> <p>Are the descriptions and characterizations direct or indirect?</p> <p>Both, towards the beginning of the essay there are a lot of direct characterizations and descriptions, but as the plot grows I think it becomes more indirect.</p> </li> <li> <p>How would you describe the relationship between mother and daughter?</p> <p>The daughter at the time trusts her mom, but as of now she seems to be ashamed of her.</p> </li> <li> <p>How do the characters change throughout the story?</p> <p>The girl seems to mature throughout the story. Originally, she seems to just follow her mom around, kind of like in an blind, aimless sense. Towards the end, she accepts that she\u2019s on her own.</p> </li> <li> <p>Do you see some characters differently form the way they see themselves?</p> <p>I think so. The girl views her mom as someone she\u2019s ashamed as, which I wouldn\u2019t totally agree with judging from the given context. Her mom seems to strive to ensure that her daughter is educated, even if there are many challenges in the way. Not all parents would be willing to go through so many hoops to ensure that their kids get good and high quality education.</p> </li> </ol>"},{"location":"ap-literature/assignments/everyday-use.html","title":"Everyday Use","text":""},{"location":"ap-literature/assignments/everyday-use.html#prompt","title":"Prompt","text":"<p>Shakespeare's Juliet wonders, perhaps naively, \"What's in a name?\" In many works of literature, the answer is \"much.\" Characters' names denote or simply suggest personal qualities. They may also reflect larger thematic considerations. Reflect on the characters in Alice Walker's \"Everday Use.\" Write one paragraph (8-10 sentences) where you analyze the ways in which characters' names illustrate the meaning of the story as a whole.</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/assignments/everyday-use.html#response","title":"Response","text":"<p>While reading the text, it jumped out to me how the narrator was referring to each person. For example, right after the Dee tells her (the narrator) her new-found name, she immediately refers to her in the narration by her new name, which is just interesting as the narrator has probably called her Dee since she was born. The same can also be seen when she learns the pronunciation of Dee\u2019s boyfriend\u2019s name, she immediately refers to him as Hakim-a-barber. Eventually, she even refers to him just as \u201cbarber.\u201d</p> <p>On a much deeper note, Dee\u2019s name change seems to have little to no value/no effect on who she was originally. Maggie on the other hand, retains her name - as there was no \u201creason\u201d to change it to begin with. After the whole incident with the quilt/who gets to keep it, you could say that Maggie and the narrator know the \u201ctrue value\u201d of the quilt, the rich family history and legacy. Dee however, is rather hypocritical. On one hand, she claims that the quilt is her legacy, yet she changes her name - even though she was named after her relative, \u201cBig Dee\u201d. The narrator in this story uses names to display a rather stark contrast between the characters who understand the meaning of \u201clegacy\u201d versus ones who only have a surface level appreciation.</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/assignments/hills-like-white-elephants-pov.html","title":"Hills Like White Elephants POV Questions","text":""},{"location":"ap-literature/assignments/hills-like-white-elephants-pov.html#prompt","title":"Prompt","text":"<ol> <li> <p>The main topic of discussion between the man and the girl is never named. What is the \"awfully simple operation\"? Why    is it not named? What different attitudes are taken toward it by the man and the girl? Why?</p> </li> <li> <p>Though the story consists mostly of dialogue, and though it contains strong emotional conflict, it is entirely    without adverbs, indicating tone of remarks. How does Hemingway indicate tone? Where do you see the characters being    insincere? Ironic or sarcastic?</p> </li> <li> <p>Much of the conversation seems to be about trivial things (ordering drinks, the weather, etc.). What purposes does    this conversation serve? What relevance does the girl's remark about Absinthe have?</p> </li> <li> <p>What is the point of the comparison of the hills to white elephants? Why does the author use it as a title?</p> </li> <li> <p>Which character seems more reasonable? Who \"wins\" the conflict?</p> </li> <li> <p>According to the definitions presented in the book, what is the point of view used in this story?</p> </li> </ol>"},{"location":"ap-literature/assignments/hills-like-white-elephants-pov.html#response","title":"Response","text":"<ol> <li> <p>The operation being discussed is strongly implied to be an abortion, although the term is never explicitly used. The    absence of the term may serve to heighten the tension and uncertainty between the characters, reflecting societal    taboos or the couple's own discomfort in facing the issue directly. The man seems to trivialize the operation,    calling it \"awfully simple,\" likely in an attempt to persuade Jig to go through with it. Jig appears to be more    ambivalent and possibly more aware of the emotional and moral complexity of the decision.</p> </li> <li> <p>Hemingway uses other techniques to indicate tone, including the characters' actions and what they choose to say or    not say. The lack of adverbs forces the reader to infer tone from context, making the dialogue more open to    interpretation. Insincerity is evident when the man insists he wants Jig to do what she wants, while his continued    pressure indicates he has a preferred outcome. Moments of irony or sarcasm occur when Jig makes remarks like, \"Then    I'll do it. Because I don't care about me.\"</p> </li> <li> <p>The conversation about drinks and the weather serves as a diversion and a way to manage the tension and emotional    gravity of the real issue at hand. It also serves to contrast the mundane aspects of life with the life-changing    decision they are facing. Jig's remark about Absinthe\u2014another strong alcohol\u2014may indicate a desire for escape or    numbness, given the weight of the decision she's facing.</p> </li> <li> <p>The comparison of the hills to white elephants serves as a metaphor for the situation the couple finds themselves    in\u2014facing an issue that is large, hard to ignore, but also hard to talk about directly. The term \"white elephant\"    generally refers to something that is more of a burden than a blessing, which could apply to how the characters are    viewing the potential child or even their relationship. The title serves to encapsulate the emotional and symbolic    weight of the story.</p> </li> <li> <p>Reasonableness is subjective and depends on one's viewpoint on the issue. The man seems to be logical but emotionally    detached, while Jig appears more emotionally tuned into the complexity of the situation. Neither clearly \"wins\" the    conflict; the story ends ambiguously, and the power dynamics are left unresolved.</p> </li> <li> <p>The point of view used in \"Hills Like White Elephants\" is third-person limited objective. The narrator reports the    events and dialogue without providing direct insight into the characters' thoughts or feelings, leaving it to the    reader to interpret the emotional nuances.</p> </li> </ol>"},{"location":"ap-literature/assignments/walker-mansfield-joyce.html","title":"Walker, Mansfield, Joyce Text","text":""},{"location":"ap-literature/assignments/walker-mansfield-joyce.html#walker-everyday-use","title":"Walker - Everyday Use","text":"<ol> <li>Does the mother's refusal to let Dee have the quilts indicate a permanent or temporary change of character? Why has    she never done anything like it before? Why does she do it now? What details in the story prepare for and foreshadow    the refusal?</li> </ol> <p>I think that the mother\u2019s refusal to let Dee have the quilts is rather a permanent shift in character. As one of the    more climatic elements within the story, this is one of the first time the mom stands up against Dee. She is standing    up for her own views and perception of family heritance and legacy. Dee, pictured as the \u201cperfect sister\u201d, as she\u2019s    educated and confident, when compared to her sister Maggie, \u201cthe ugly duckling\u201d, has probably never had this moment    before, which is what makes this moment so climatic and significant. The mom may have felt inferior to Dee, which is    why she probably let Dee kind of roll over her in the past.</p> <p>The mom recognizes the genuine connection Maggie has with the quilts and their shared heritage - compared with Dee\u2019s    surface level understanding. Understanding that the quilts hold more meaning than mere decorative artifacts is    probably one of the core reasons. By giving the quilts to Maggie, the mom is actually honoring the tradition/legacy.</p> <p>Some details that could foreshadow this is the name change that Dee goes through. The name change could symbolize her    being disconnected from the true meaning of what the quilts meant.</p> <ol> <li>Locate examples of direct and indirect characterization. Why does the author use both methods in this story?</li> </ol> <p>Direct characterization: \"a large, big-boned woman with rough, man-working hands.\u201d</p> <p>Indirect characterization: \u201cShe has been like this, chin on chest, eyes on ground, feet in shuffle, ever since the    fire that burned the other house to the ground.\u201d It can be inferred that Maggie has mentally been scarred from this,    which gives her a timid/shy personality.</p> <ol> <li>Which characters are fully developed, and which are \"flat\"? Is there a \"developing\" character here? 9) Where is the    epiphany in the story? What makes this moment in the story effective?</li> </ol> <p>I would say that Dee and the mom could be fully developed characters. Both of these characters have more to them than    2 traits. They both already know what they want, and their overall personality doesn\u2019t gain/improve significantly    after this plot. While you could argue that the mom\u2019s personality is also developing (after rejecting Dee\u2019s request),    I think that her mindset regarding Dee has still been the same, she was never just able to voice it out/stand up to    Dee about it. Her motives were probably the same.</p> <p>Maggie may be considered a developing character, as when the mom stands up for her, she may gain confidence and    understand the meaning of the heritage associated with the quilts.</p> <p>Flat characters would be the boyfriend. All he does is just show that Dee has changed, doesn\u2019t add to much to the    plot and his personality is still relatively vague.</p> <p>The epiphany is the moment of realization when the mom realizes that she should stand up for Maggie and have the    quilts go to her rather than Dee. This is effective as this is the action that generates the overall theme of the    story - it prompts us as the audience to question the true meaning of heritage.</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/assignments/walker-mansfield-joyce.html#araby-james-joyce","title":"Araby - James Joyce","text":"<ol> <li>How is the boy characterized? Roughly how old is he and how would you describe his temperament and personality?</li> </ol> <p>The boy is characterized as a youthful boy - he views the world sort of in an immature lens, that hopefully his    dreams can become reality. I would say that he seems to be around our age or a bit younger. His personality is    heavily affected by the fact that he is so young - he dreams about the ideal romantic relationship, which sort of    embodies the innocence of youth. At some point, the girl is basically the center of his universe - which kind of    shows his immaturity too I guess.</p> <ol> <li>Analyze the role of Mangan's sister. Why is she not given a name? How does her physical description relate to the    boy's state of mind?</li> </ol> <p>Mangan\u2019s sister is who the boy is obsessed with and simping over, basically \u201chis dreams.\u201d I think by not having a    specific name tied with the character, it allows us as readers to associate that character with one that we\u2019ve had in    our own lives - it provides a very general view to the audience. Her physical description is kind of vague, nothing    specific, except for that she was basically the boy\u2019s dream/ideal figure.</p> <ol> <li>Describe the role of the boy's uncle. Can he be called the antagonist? When the uncle returns home, he is talking to    himself and moving awkwardly. What are these \"signs\" the boy says he is able to interpret?</li> </ol> <p>The boy\u2019s uncle kind of plays the role of like a reality check to the boy, especially with him being late which    wouldn\u2019t allow the boy to continue forward with his plans. I don\u2019t think it\u2019s necessarily fair to call him the    antagonist, however his actions do prevent the protagonist from accomplishing his goals.</p> <p>The uncle seems to be drunk, which seems to be a common occurrence.</p> <ol> <li>Analyze the boy's feelings as described in the last paragraph. Are his feelings justified? How will he be changed as    a result of his experience at the bazaar?</li> </ol> <p>He feels down, as his dreams are sort of crushed by his realization. All of the thoughts he had previously about the    girl, his plans, all failed, and he is hit with a dose of reality.</p> <p>I think his feelings are unrealistic - there was no way the bazaar would have allowed him to accomplish his goals.    However, I think from the perspective of the boy, who doesn\u2019t have much life experience, his feelings would make    sense his feelings seemed to be very real and genuine.</p> <p>Hopefully from this experience, the boy will mature and develop more realistic and attainable goals, rather than    idolizing someone. While reality is sometimes difficult to accept, we all learn to accept it anyways.</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html","title":"Character and Plot","text":""},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#commercial-vs-literary-fiction","title":"Commercial vs. Literary Fiction","text":"<p>Commercial fiction is solely used to entertain or make money</p> <p>Literary Fiction has artistic intentions looking to yield and entertain but also understanding - broaden, deepen, and sharpen the reader\u2019s awareness of life</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#characters","title":"Characters","text":"<p>Protagonist, Antagonist</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#revealing-characters","title":"Revealing Characters","text":"<p>Physical, emotional psychological, dialogue, behavior will all contribute to how a character is portrayed</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#direct-characterization","title":"Direct Characterization","text":"<p>When a narrator explicitly describes the background, motivation, temperament</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#indirect-characterization","title":"Indirect Characterization","text":"<p>Author requires the audience to infer what a character is like through what the character says, thinks, or others say</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#narrative-structure","title":"Narrative Structure","text":"<p>Coming of age story (bildungsroman) - shows how the young character grows from innocence to experience</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#epiphany","title":"Epiphany","text":"<p>A pivotal realization about life</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#commercial-fiction-characters","title":"Commercial Fiction Characters","text":""},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#main-character","title":"Main Character","text":"<ul> <li>Less easily labeled and pigeonholed</li> <li>Could be wholly unsympathetic or even despicable</li> <li>Deals with characters who have both \u201cgood\u201d and \u201cevil\u201d impulses; three -dimensional</li> <li>Allow the reader to observe human nature in complexity &amp; multiplicity</li> <li>Good writers \u201cshow, not tell,\u201d which allow the characters to be dramatized</li> </ul>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#consistent-with-behavior","title":"Consistent with Behavior","text":"<ul> <li>Attractive and sympathetic</li> <li>Not perfect, but fundamentally decent, honest good-hearted, and preferable good-looking</li> <li>May have larger-than-life qualities or defy laws of \u201cordinary \u201c people</li> <li>Vices must be willing to be accepted by the reader (e.g. James Bond)</li> </ul>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#character-categories","title":"Character Categories","text":""},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#flat-characters","title":"Flat Characters","text":"<p>Only have one or two predominant traits; summed up in a sentence or two</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#round-characters","title":"Round Characters","text":"<p>Complex &amp; many-sided</p> <p>Tip</p> <p>Most short stories will only have one or two round characters; minor characters must primarily remain flat</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#stock-characters","title":"Stock Characters","text":"<ul> <li>Stereotyped figures that appear in fiction, so we recognize them immediately</li> <li>The strong, silent sheriff, glamorous international spy, the cruel stepmother, mad scientist, brilliant, eccentric   detective</li> </ul>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#static-character","title":"Static Character","text":"<p>Remains the same person from beginning to end</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#developing-dynamic-character","title":"Developing &amp; Dynamic Character","text":"<p>Undergoes some distinct change of character, personality, or outlook</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#setting","title":"Setting","text":"<ul> <li>Time and place, the when and where of a literary text</li> <li>\u201cBedrock\u201d or \u201charmony\u201d of a narrative on which the characters or soloists of the story are maneuvered</li> <li>Includes objective facts - community or nation, date and time, weather, and season</li> <li>Setting should illuminate character, not the other way around</li> <li>Author will often contrast character\u2019s emotions with the setting</li> <li> <p>Consider how the setting takes place to the story as whole by examining details that might seem physical and objective</p> <p>Example</p> <p>Winter transitions into  spring - new beginnings</p> </li> <li> <p>Highlight the details - the sights and sounds, textures, and tones, colors, and shape - because they often depict more about the setting than a when and where</p> </li> </ul>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#plot-and-structure","title":"Plot and Structure","text":"<p>Authors arrange conflicts and resolutions to create logical patterns of cause-and-effect and to develop characters\u2019 relationships with each other. Conflicts are then born from these relationships</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#basic-narrative-structure","title":"Basic Narrative Structure","text":""},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#exposition","title":"Exposition","text":"<p>Opening section that provide background information about characters, setting and basic situation</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#rising-action","title":"Rising Action","text":"<p>After an inciting incident or even, the conflict and complications the main character experiences begin to build</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#climax","title":"Climax","text":"<p>The emotional tension or suspense of the plot reaches its peak</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#falling-action","title":"Falling Action","text":"<p>Details the result (or fallout) of the climax or turning point</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#denouement-resolution","title":"Denouement (Resolution)","text":"<p>\u201cUntying the not\u201d balance is restored to the world after conflict has been resolved - many authors leave this \u201cunfinished\u201d so readers can construct their own meaning at the end of the story</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#strategies-of-structure","title":"Strategies of Structure","text":""},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#immediate-introduction","title":"Immediate Introduction","text":"<p>Conflict is introduced immediately, from the start</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#flashbacks","title":"Flashbacks","text":"<p>Describe events that have already taken place</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/characters-and-plot.html#foreshadowing","title":"Foreshadowing","text":"<p>Hinting at events that will happen later in the story</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/narrative-perspective-pov.html","title":"Narrative Perspective &amp; Point of View","text":"<p>All focus on who tells the story, how they tell it, and how they and we, as readers, understand their roles in the narrative</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/narrative-perspective-pov.html#point-of-view","title":"Point of View","text":"<p>The position from which a narrator relates the events of a narrative</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/narrative-perspective-pov.html#first-person","title":"First Person","text":"<p>Uses first-person pronouns such as I and we. See the story through the lens of one character. Usually the main character, though it could be a minor one too.</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/narrative-perspective-pov.html#second-person","title":"Second Person","text":"<p>Puts the reader directly into the story; rarely used, could be viewed as gimmicky because it  makes the reading too literal. However, it can create intimacy</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/narrative-perspective-pov.html#third-person","title":"Third Person","text":"<p>Tells the story with third-person pronouns - he, she, and it. Views all events from a distance.</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/narrative-perspective-pov.html#limited","title":"Limited","text":"<p>Views all events from one person's perspective; good insight into how that character views the world</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/narrative-perspective-pov.html#omniscient","title":"Omniscient","text":"<p>Views and knows events from perspectives of multiple characters.</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/narrative-perspective-pov.html#objective","title":"Objective","text":"<p>Most neutral and impartial. Does not follow a single character or enter one's perspective. Don't know what characters are thinking or feeling.</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/theme.html","title":"Theme","text":"<p>Controlling idea or its central insight, generally a unifying generalization about life state or implied by the story</p> <p>To derive the theme, we must determine its central purpose - what view o flife it supposrts or what insight into life it reveals.</p> <p>Note</p> <p>There is no prescribed method for discovering them.</p>"},{"location":"ap-literature/notes/theme.html#thematic-principles","title":"Thematic Principles","text":"<p>Theme should be expressible in the form of a statement with a subject + predicate</p> <p>Example</p> <p>Loyalty to a country often inspires heroic self-sacrifice.</p> <p>Theme should be stated as a generalization about life</p> <p>No specific name sof people or place from the text</p> <p>Must not make the generalization larger than is justified by the terms of the story</p> <p>Avoid absolutes (every, all always, never; etc.) and instead use modifiers (som, sometimes, often, may, etc.)</p> <p>There is no one way of stating the theme of a story It merely presents a view of life, if the previous criteria are met</p> <p>Avoid using statements that reduce the theme to a familiar saying, latitude, or clich\u00e9</p> <p>Example</p> <p>You can't judge a book by its cover</p> <p>A stitch in time saves nine.</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html","title":"Chapter 1: Collecting Data in Reasonable Ways","text":"<p>To begin statistics, you first must ask question about a population, then collect data</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#collecting-data","title":"Collecting Data","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#types-of-studies","title":"Types of Studies","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#experimental","title":"Experimental","text":"<p>Experimental studies comprise of experiments. Typical features of an experimental study will comprise of control of different conditions, and typically won\u2019t give *freedom* to the participants</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#observational","title":"Observational","text":"<p>Examples of observational studies would be polling, surveying, research, or simulations. Typical features of an observational study will comprise of no control, just *observing*, and has a sense of freedom</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#sampling","title":"Sampling","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#census","title":"Census","text":"<p>Counts everything, take the U.S. Census for example, which gathers statistics (ideally) for every American. Some cons about this sampling method is that it is too resource intensive ******and not cost effective</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#samples","title":"Samples","text":"<p>Therefore, if a census cannot be done, you want to choose a smaller set, known as a sample. Note that it must be representative.</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#parameter-and-statistics","title":"Parameter and Statistics","text":"<p>Population Characteristic (Parameter): The number that represents population (the value of the population).</p> <p>Statistics: The number that represents the sample</p> <p>Tip</p> <p>Parameter requires census, while statistic requires the sample</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#methods-for-sampling","title":"Methods for Sampling","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#simple-random-sample-srs","title":"Simple Random Sample (SRS)","text":"<p>Example: Using a computer as a random number generator, names in a bucket, etc.</p> <p>Cons: By randomness, you may get similar (homogeneous) people, repeats</p> <p>Warning</p> <p>Ensure whether or not you need to include \u201cwithout replacement\u201d</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#stratified-random-sample","title":"Stratified Random Sample","text":"<p>Group people/objects into \u201cstrata\u201d that are homogeneous, then SRS each group.</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#cluster-sampling","title":"Cluster Sampling","text":"<p>Group people/objects into clusters that are non-homogeneous (choose a group where people/objects may inherently be different, then SRS the cluster, census people within the cluster</p> <p>Examples would include classroom or community</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#convenience-sample","title":"Convenience Sample","text":"<p>A very easy way to sample, but terrible. Consists of using whatever is the most accessible</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#systematic-sample","title":"Systematic Sample","text":"<p>Systematically select people (e.g every 10 people)</p> <p>Isn\u2019t the most ideal as you could possibility of over-represent people</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#biases","title":"Biases","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#voluntary-response-bias","title":"Voluntary Response Bias","text":"<p>A type of bias which involves volunteering. The problem with this is is that it will often result with samples dominated by strongly opinionated people</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#non-response-bias","title":"Non-response Bias","text":"<p>People who aren\u2019t responding might have an affect</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#undercoverage-bias-selection-bias","title":"Undercoverage Bias (Selection Bias)","text":"<p>The way of choosing people intentionally leaves out people</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#response-bias-question-wording","title":"Response Bias (Question Wording)","text":"<p>Twisting the truth, framing the question in such manner so that it may result in bias towards specific response(s)</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#experimental-studies","title":"Experimental Studies","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#experimental-design","title":"Experimental Design","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#terms","title":"Terms","text":"<p>Treatments: Experimental Conditions</p> <p>Explanatory Variable: Variable that is manipulated</p> <p>Response Variable: Variable which is affected</p> <p>Experimental Unit: Person/object receiving treatment</p> <p>Replication: Many experimental units</p> <p>Confounding Variable: Things that might affect the result</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#direct-control","title":"Direct Control","text":"<p>Make variables as much as the same as possible (will consist of variables you can control)</p> <p>Variables you cannot control would go to random assignment to treatments</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#methods-for-assigning-treatments","title":"Methods for Assigning Treatments","text":"<p>Completely Randomized Design: Everything is randomized</p> <p>Randomized Block Design: Assign treatments to units (random within each block) in each block</p>  \ud83d\udca1 Blocks are groups that or homogeneous, like strata"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#placebo","title":"Placebo","text":"<p>Treatment that looks real, but should do nothing. This is often, but not always, a form of control group, and is typically used within medicine</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#blinding","title":"Blinding","text":"<p>Single Blind: People do not know which treatment they received</p> <p>Double Blind: People/person giving treatments do not know</p>  \ud83d\udca1 Not all experiments are able to be blind"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-1.html#study-conclusions","title":"Study Conclusions","text":"<p>Experimental Study Conclusion: Cause and Effect relationship, otherwise known as causation</p> <p>Observational Study Conclusion: Association (correlation)</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-2.html","title":"Chapter 2: Graphical Methods for Describing Data Distributions","text":"<p>After asking a question and collecting data, the next step would be display and analyze data</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-2.html#data-types","title":"Data Types","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-2.html#categorical-data","title":"Categorical Data","text":"<p>Data which is in words. Examples would include yes, no, favourite color, etc.</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-2.html#numerical-data","title":"Numerical Data","text":"<p>Data in numbers</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-2.html#discrete","title":"Discrete","text":"<p>Only $n$ numbers (countable)</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-2.html#continuous","title":"Continuous","text":"<p>Any numeric value</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-2.html#displaying-data","title":"Displaying Data","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-2.html#bar-chart","title":"Bar Chart","text":"<p>y-axis: frequency or relative frequency (otherwise known as percentage)</p> <p>The bars are separated and can be in any order</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-2.html#comparative-bar-chart","title":"Comparative Bar Chart","text":"<p>Features two or more bars stacked beside each other to compare. y-axis will typically be relative frequency as there may be size differences</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-2.html#describing-bar-charts","title":"Describing Bar Charts","text":"<p>Which categories are bigger or smaller, and if comparative, what are the difference and similarities between categories</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-2.html#numerical-data_1","title":"Numerical Data","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-2.html#dot-plot","title":"Dot Plot","text":"<p>Number line with dots (stack dots if more than one occurrence)</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-2.html#histogram","title":"Histogram","text":"<p>Typically have ranges/relative frequency. Some features of histograms is that precise data is hidden, but it allows for quick summary. The rectangles on the histogram are touching, compared to a bar chart. Additionally, the x-axis is typically continuous numerical, with each bar ranging from $[a,b)$. For situations involving discrete numerical, the label is kept in the center</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-2.html#stem-and-leaf","title":"Stem and Leaf","text":"<p>Comprised of a table, with the stem defining each leaf. Typically will have a legend and example, and no commas are used unless there are multi-digits</p> Stem Leaf 1 2 3 4 2 5 6 7"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-2.html#comparative-stem-and-leaf","title":"Comparative Stem and Leaf","text":"<p>Two stem and leaf charts, with a shared leaf column. The left group will ascend from right to left</p> Group A Stem Group B 6 5 4 2 1 2 3 3 2 1 3 4 5 6"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-2.html#cumulative-relative-frequency-plot","title":"Cumulative Relative Frequency Plot","text":"<p>Most noticeable features would include only positive slope, as well as the y-axis typically ending at 100% or at any equivalent</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-2.html#time-series-plots","title":"Time Series Plots","text":"<p>The x-axis is typically time, y-axis is observed value. Features connected line segments</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-2.html#describing-distributions","title":"Describing Distributions","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-2.html#shapes","title":"Shapes","text":"<p>Unimodal</p> <p>One center hump, can be referred as approximately symmetric or a bell curve</p> <p>Left Skew</p> <p>Most of the data lies on the right</p> <p>Right Skew</p> <p>Most of the data lies on the left</p> <p>Bimodal</p> <p>Two humps</p> <p>Multi-modal</p> <p>Multiple humps</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-2.html#socs","title":"SOCS","text":"<p>Shape: Examples would include bell curve, approximately symmetric, skew, bimodal, and multimodal (including outliers)</p> <p>Outliers: Extreme values</p> <p>Center: Where most of the data is (in most cases, this would either be median or mean)</p> <p>Spread: High/Low Spread</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-2.html#bivariable-numerical-data","title":"Bivariable Numerical Data","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-2.html#scatter-plots","title":"Scatter Plots","text":"<p>Select one variable which causes y to change, typically with the $y \\text{ vs } x$ format</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-3.html","title":"Chapter 3: Numerical Methods for Describing Data Distributions","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-3.html#terms-definitions","title":"Terms Definitions","text":"<p>Sample mean $\\bar{x}$: Average from sample</p> <p>Population mean $\\mu$: Average from population</p> <p>Median: Middle number</p> <p>Interquartile Range: (3rd quartile - 1st quartile). Otherwise known as the range of the middle 50% of data</p> <p>Population Standard Deviation $\\sigma$: The average deviation from the mean</p> <p>Population Variance is $\\sigma^2$</p> <p>$$ \\sigma=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\Sigma(x-\\bar{x})^2}{n-1}} $$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-3.html#interpretations","title":"Interpretations","text":"<p>The mean value of (# with unit) represents the typical value of (variable name)</p> <p>The standard deviation (# with unit) is the amount on average, the values of (variable name with measurement) deviate from the mean. This indicates (high/low) variability</p> <p>The median values of (# with unit) indicates that 50% of the data is above (# with unit) and 50% of the data is below (# with unit)</p> <p>The IQR of (# with unit) is the range of the middle 50% of the data</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-3.html#box-plots","title":"Box Plots","text":"<p>In statistics there are two types of centers that one may choose to use: sample mean $\\bar{x}$, or median</p> <p>A box plot must describe the minimum value, quartile 1, median, quartile 3, and max.</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-3.html#guessing-median-values","title":"Guessing Median Values","text":"<p>When $\\int_a^bB(x)dx=\\int_b^cB(x)dx$, the median exists at $b$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-3.html#outliers","title":"Outliers","text":"<p>An outlier $x$ will exist under the following conditions</p> <p>$$ x&gt;Q_3+1.5IQR \\text{ or } x&lt;Q_1+1.5IQR $$</p> <p>Warning</p> <p>It is important to note that it is only greater or less than. Equal to does not constitute to an outlier</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-3.html#normal-curves","title":"Normal Curves","text":"<p>Normal curves are unimodal, symmetrical distributions, oftentimes referred to as a bell curve. The area under the curve is typically used to represent distributions.</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-3.html#empirical-rule","title":"Empirical Rule","text":"<p>$$ (-\\sigma, \\sigma) \\approx 68\\% \\\\ (-2\\sigma, 2\\sigma) \\approx 95\\% \\\\ (-3\\sigma, 3\\sigma) \\approx 99.7\\% $$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-3.html#z-scores","title":"z-scores","text":"<p>Describes the number of standard deviations $\\sigma$ a value is above or below a mean data point</p> <p>$$ z=\\frac{x-\\mu}{\\sigma} $$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-3.html#percentiles","title":"Percentiles","text":"<p>The $n$th percentile is defined as the number where $n\\%$ of the data is below. Keep in mind that high percentile isn\u2019t always ideal</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-3.html#standard-normal-curve","title":"Standard Normal Curve","text":"<p>The standard normal curve is when $\\mu=0$ and $\\sigma = 1$</p> <p>Normalizing data is using the same index of the standard normal curve to find percentile</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-4.html","title":"Chapter 4: Describing Bivariate Numerical Data","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-4.html#correlation-coefficient","title":"Correlation Coefficient","text":"<p>Denoted with the variable $r$ (only for linear)</p> <ul> <li>Must be between the interval $[-1,1]$</li> </ul>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-4.html#analysis","title":"Analysis","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-4.html#linear-relationship","title":"Linear Relationship","text":"<p>When $r\\ge0$, there is positive linear relationship</p> <p>When $r\\le0$, there is negative linear relationship.</p> <p>When $r=0$, there is no linear relationship and is perfectly random</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-4.html#perfect-positive-and-negative-correlation","title":"Perfect Positive and Negative Correlation","text":"<p>When $r=1$, there is perfect correlation</p> <p>When $r=-1$, there is perfect negative correlation.</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-4.html#interpretation","title":"Interpretation","text":"<p>The correlation coefficient of (r-value) indicates a (strong/moderate/weak) (positive/negative) linear relationship between (y-var) and (x-var)</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-4.html#best-line-of-fit-least-squares-regression-line","title":"Best Line of Fit (Least Squares Regression Line)","text":"<p>When $\\Sigma\\text{residual}^2$ is the least</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-4.html#residuals","title":"Residuals","text":"<p>A residual is defined as the $\\text{actual}-\\text{predicted}$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-4.html#residual-plots","title":"Residual Plots","text":"<p>Occurs after a regression, which can be used to determine whether a regression is fit for a specific model</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-4.html#regressions","title":"Regressions","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-4.html#form","title":"Form","text":"<p>$$ \\hat{y}=a+bx $$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-4.html#interpretation_1","title":"Interpretation","text":"<p>The slope of the least squares regression line is (slope). This means for an increase in 1 (unit) in (x-var), there is an (increase/decrease) of (# with unit) in the predicted (y-var)</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-4.html#influential-points","title":"Influential Points","text":"<p>High Leverage Points: Totally change and has a big effect on the regression line, typically a large x-value</p> <p>Outlier: Extreme y-value (does not effect x-value)</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-4.html#coefficient-of-determination-r2","title":"Coefficient of Determination $r^2$","text":"<p>Answers how much a linear relationship can be explained by a variable, with $r^2 \\in [0,1]$</p> <p>Approximately ($r^2$) of the variability of (y-var) can be explained by the linear relationship between (y-var) and (x-var)</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-5.html","title":"Chapter 5: Probability","text":"<p>Probability describes the chance an event occurs over the long run</p> <p>$$ P(A)\\in[0,1]\\\\ P(A\\mid B)=P(A)+P(B)\\\\ P(!A)=1-P(A) $$</p> <p>Law of large numbers: As the number of observations increases, the proportion of the occurrence approaches $P(A)$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-5.html#conditional-probability","title":"Conditional Probability","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-5.html#definitions","title":"Definitions","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-5.html#or-condition","title":"Or Condition","text":"<p>Probability of A or B occurring</p> <p>If independent:</p> <p>$$ P(A\\cup B)=P(A)+P(B) $$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-5.html#and-condition","title":"And Condition","text":"<p>Probability of A and B occurring</p> <p>If independent:</p> <p>$$ P(A \\cap B)=P(A) \\times P(B) $$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-5.html#given-condition","title":"Given Condition","text":"<p>Probably of A given B has occurred.</p> <p>$$ P(A \\mid B) = \\frac{P(A \\cap B)}{P(B)} $$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-5.html#testing-independence","title":"Testing Independence","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-6.html","title":"Chapter 6: Random Variables and Probability Distributions","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-6.html#random-variables","title":"Random Variables","text":"<p>Random variables are defined as a variable that depends on the outcomes of a chance experiment, which are numerical values</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-6.html#types-of-random-variables","title":"Types of Random Variables","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-6.html#discrete","title":"Discrete","text":"<p>Variables which are measurable and countable</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-6.html#continuous","title":"Continuous","text":"<p>Variables which can consist of any numeric value</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-6.html#properties-of-probability-distributions","title":"Properties of Probability Distributions","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-6.html#expected-values-and-standard-deviations","title":"Expected Values and Standard Deviations","text":"<p>$$ E=\\Sigma x\\times p(x)\\ \\sigma_x=\\Sigma(x-\\mu_x)^2p(x) $$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-6.html#linear-combinations","title":"Linear Combinations","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-6.html#properties-of-data-points","title":"Properties of Data Points","text":"<p>Let $x$ be any data point, and $c$ any constant</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-6.html#addition-and-subtraction","title":"Addition and Subtraction","text":"<p>Represented by $x+c$</p> <p>$$ \\mu =\\mu+c\\ \\sigma=\\sigma $$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-6.html#multiplication-and-subtraction","title":"Multiplication and Subtraction","text":"<p>Represented with $xc$</p> <p>$$ \\mu=c\\mu\\ \\sigma=c\\sigma $$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-6.html#variances-and-standard-deviations","title":"Variances and Standard Deviations","text":"<p>$$ \\sigma^2=\\Sigma\\sigma^2\\ \\therefore\\sigma=\\sqrt{\\Sigma\\sigma^2} $$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-6.html#distributions","title":"Distributions","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-6.html#binomial-distributions","title":"Binomial Distributions","text":"<p>Binomial distributions have two possibilities, most commonly true or false. $P(\\text{success})$ must be constant every round, trials must be independent, and there are a finite amount of trials</p> <p>$$ \\mu_x=np\\ \\sigma_x=\\sqrt{np(1-p)} $$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-6.html#geometric-distributions","title":"Geometric Distributions","text":"<p>Geometric distributions have two possibilities, most commonly true or false. $P(\\text{success})$ must be constant every round, trials must be independent, you keep going until first success. Geometric distributions must atleast have one trial</p> <p>$$ P(x)=(1-P(s))^{n-1}P(s)\\ \\mu_x=\\frac{1}{p}\\ \\sigma_x=\\frac{\\sqrt{1-p}}{p} $$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-6.html#normal-distributions","title":"Normal Distributions","text":"<p>Combination of two normal distributions</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-8.html","title":"Chapter 8: Sampling Variability and Sampling Distributions","text":"<p>After asking a question, collecting data, analyzing, and probability, the next step would be inference</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-8.html#inference","title":"Inference","text":"<p>Typically consists of comparing populations (or different in proportions) and means (or difference in means).</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-8.html#populations","title":"Populations","text":"<p>Census will result in the true proportion, represented by $p$. The estimate proportion, from a sample, is denoted with $\\hat{p}$</p> <p>Question</p> <p>$p\\ne\\hat{p}$, as the sampling procedure is not a census, the sample size is different, there could be response bias, and sampling variability</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-8.html#sampling-distribution","title":"Sampling Distribution","text":"<p>A random sample of size $n$, repeated every possibile combination of size $n$, will typically result in a trillions of sample.</p> <p>Warning</p> <p>Sample distribution and sampling distributions are different. Sampling distributions are for multiple samples</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chapter-8.html#estimators","title":"Estimators","text":"<p>An estimator is a method or formula on some small data to determine the true value. It would be ideal to have it centered around the true value, which would be defined as an unbiased estimator.</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chi-sqaured-tests.html","title":"Chi-Squared Tests","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chi-sqaured-tests.html#chi-squared-tests_1","title":"Chi Squared Tests","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chi-sqaured-tests.html#goodness-of-fit","title":"Goodness of Fit","text":"<p>Use when 1 variable, many categories, 1 sample</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chi-sqaured-tests.html#hypothesis","title":"Hypothesis","text":"<p>$h_0:p_1=p_2=p_n...$ or $p_1=..., p_2=..., p_n=...$</p> <p>$h_a:$ At least $n$ proportions are wrong</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chi-sqaured-tests.html#conditions","title":"Conditions","text":"<ul> <li>Expected count $(E) \\ge 5$</li> <li>Random or representative</li> </ul>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chi-sqaured-tests.html#equations","title":"Equations","text":"<p>$$ \\large \\chi^2=\\Sigma{\\frac{(O-E)^2}{E}} $$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chi-sqaured-tests.html#independence","title":"Independence","text":"<p>Use when 2 variables and 1 sample</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chi-sqaured-tests.html#hypothesis_1","title":"Hypothesis","text":"<p>$h_0:$ Variable 1 and variable two are independent</p> <p>$h_a:$ Variable 1 and variable two are dependent</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chi-sqaured-tests.html#conditions_1","title":"Conditions","text":"<p>Random or representative, and expected count $(E) \\ge 5$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chi-sqaured-tests.html#equations_1","title":"Equations","text":"<p>$$ E=\\frac{(\\text{row})(\\text{column})}{\\text{grand total}} $$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chi-sqaured-tests.html#homogeneity","title":"Homogeneity","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/chi-sqaured-tests.html#descriptors","title":"Descriptors","text":"<p>Use when 1 variable, many categories, and multiple samples</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/chi-sqaured-tests.html#hypothesis_2","title":"Hypothesis","text":"<p>$h_0:$ Category proportions are the same across each population</p> <p>$h_a:$ Category proportions are not the same across each population</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/inference.html","title":"Statistical Inference Methods","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/inference.html#proportional","title":"Proportional","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/inference.html#confidence-interval","title":"Confidence Interval","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/inference.html#one-sample-z-interval","title":"One Sample z-interval","text":"<p>Conditions:</p> <ul> <li>Random/Representative Sample</li> <li>Independent Samples</li> <li>Normality: $n\\hat{p}\\ge10$ and $n(1-\\hat{p})\\ge10$</li> </ul> <p>$$ \\hat{p} \\pm z^\\star\\sqrt{\\frac{\\hat{p}(1-\\hat{p})}{n}}</p> <p>$$</p> <p>Assuming the sample was selected in a reasonable manner, we are CLEVEL% confident that the actual proportion of VAR is between LOW and HIGH</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/inference.html#two-sample-z-interval","title":"Two Sample z-interval","text":"<ul> <li>Both random/representative samples</li> <li>Both independent samples</li> <li>Normality on both samples: $n\\hat{p}\\ge10$ and $n(1-\\hat{p})\\ge10$</li> </ul> <p>$$ (\\hat{p}_1 - \\hat{p}_2) \\pm z^\\star\\sqrt{\\frac{\\hat{p}_1(1-\\hat{p}_1)}{n_1} + \\frac{\\hat{p}_2(1-\\hat{p}_2)}{n_2}} $$</p> <p>Assuming the sample was selected in a reasonable manner, we are CLEVEL% confident that the difference of proportions of VAR is between LOW and HIGH</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/inference.html#hypothesis-tests","title":"Hypothesis Tests","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/inference.html#one-sample-z-test","title":"One Sample z-test","text":"<p>$$ h_0: p=p_0</p> <p>\\</p> <p>h_a:p&gt;, \\ne, &lt; p_0 $$</p> <p>Conditions</p> <ul> <li>Random/representative samples</li> <li>Independent samples</li> <li>Normality: $n \\ge 30$</li> </ul> <p>$$ z = \\frac{\\hat{p} - p_0}{\\sqrt{\\frac{p_0(1-p_0)}{n}}} $$</p> <p>Reject $h_0$ when the p-value is less than $\\alpha$ (there is convincing evidence to support the alternative hypothesis), otherwise fail to reject (there lacks convincing evidence to support the alternative hypothesis).</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/inference.html#two-sample-z-test","title":"Two Sample z-test","text":"<p>$$ h_0: p_1=p_2</p> <p>\\</p> <p>h_a:p_1&gt;, \\ne, &lt; p_2 $$</p> <p>Conditions</p> <ul> <li>Random/representative samples</li> <li>Independent samples</li> <li>Normality: $n \\ge 30$</li> </ul> <p>$$ \\Large \\hat{p_c}=\\frac{n_1\\hat{p_1}+n_2\\hat{p_2}}{n_1+n_2} \\\\ z = \\frac{\\hat{p}_1 - \\hat{p}_2}{\\sqrt{\\frac{\\hat{p}_c(1-\\hat{p}_c)}{n_1} + \\frac{\\hat{p}_c(1-\\hat{p}_c)}{n_2}}}</p> <p>$$</p> <p>Assuming the sample was selected in a reasonable manner, we are CLEVEL% confident that the difference of proportions of VAR is between LOW and HIGH</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/inference.html#mean","title":"Mean","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/inference.html#confidence-interval_1","title":"Confidence Interval","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/inference.html#one-sample-t-interval","title":"One Sample t-interval","text":"<p>Conditions:</p> <ul> <li>Random/representative sample</li> </ul> <p>$$ \\bar{x} \\pm t^\\star\\frac{s}{\\sqrt{n}} $$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/inference.html#two-sample-t-interval-dependent-paired","title":"Two Sample t-interval (dependent &amp; paired)","text":"<p>$$ (\\bar{x}_1 - \\bar{x}_2) \\pm t^\\star \\frac{s_d}{\\sqrt{n}}</p> <p>$$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/inference.html#two-sample-t-interval-independent","title":"Two Sample t-interval (independent)","text":"<p>$$ (\\bar{x}_1 - \\bar{x}_2) \\pm t^* \\sqrt{\\frac{s_1^2}{n_1} + \\frac{s_2^2}{n_2}}</p> <p>$$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/inference.html#hypothesis-test","title":"Hypothesis Test","text":""},{"location":"ap-statistics/inference.html#one-sample-t-test","title":"One Sample t-test","text":"<p>$$ t = \\frac{\\bar{x} - \\mu_0}{\\frac{s}{\\sqrt{n}}} $$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/inference.html#two-sample-t-test-dependent","title":"Two Sample t-test (dependent)","text":"<p>$$ t^\\star = \\frac{\\bar{x_d}}{\\frac{s_d}{\\sqrt{n}}} $$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/inference.html#two-sample-t-test-independent","title":"Two Sample t-test (independent)","text":"<p>$$ t^\\star = \\frac{\\bar{x}_1 - \\bar{x}_2}{\\sqrt{\\frac{s_1^2}{n_1} + \\frac{s_2^2}{n_2}}} $$</p>"},{"location":"ap-statistics/inference.html#power-of-tests","title":"Power of Tests","text":"<p>P-Hat: Sample Proportion</p> <p>P-Naught: Hypothesized Proportion</p> <p>P: Population Proportion</p> <p>P-Vale: Probability that you would observe p-hat or something more extreme if p-naught were true</p> <p>Power of a test: Probability of h0 rejection when it is false or should be rejected $1-\\beta$. Higher power indicates smaller beta. To increase power: Increase n (increases SE - curve gets skinner), or increase alpha (increases rejection zone)</p>"},{"location":"economics/assignments/the-road-not-taken.html","title":"The Road Not Taken","text":"<p>Two roads diverged in a yellow wood, And sorry I could not travel both And be one traveler, long I stood And looked down one as far as I could To where it bent in the undergrowth;</p> <p>Then took the other, as just as fair, And having perhaps the better claim, Because it was grassy and wanted wear; Though as for that the passing there Had worn them really about the same,</p> <p>And both that morning equally lay In leaves no step had trodden black. Oh, I kept the first for another day! Yet knowing how way leads on to way, I doubted if I should ever come back.</p> <p>I shall be telling this with a sigh Somewhere ages and ages hence: Two roads diverged in a wood, and I\u2014 I took the one less traveled by, And that has made all the difference.</p>"},{"location":"economics/assignments/the-road-not-taken.html#application-to-economics","title":"Application to Economics","text":"<p>The road not taken can be interpreted as making two choices. One choice is described as a very well maintained and often traveled-upon road. The other choice describes a road which hasn\u2019t really been used. In this specific scenario, Frost takes the road which wasn\u2019t often taken - which is a sacrifice he makes, and in turn he believes he has gotten a better reward. I guess you can sum it up as risk and reward, which is something that can be applied to economics.</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html","title":"Chapter 1 Notes","text":""},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#factors-that-contribute-to-wealth","title":"Factors That Contribute To Wealth","text":"<ul> <li>Natural resources </li> <li>Labor </li> <li>Institutions</li> </ul>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#natural-resources","title":"Natural resources","text":"<p>Countries with abundant natural resources, such as oil and gas, may have an advantage in terms of economic growth. However, natural resources are not always a guarantee of wealth, as countries with few natural resources can still be wealthy if they have other advantages, such as a skilled workforce or a good education system.</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#labor","title":"Labor","text":"<p>A country's workforce is another important factor in its wealth. A country with a large and productive workforce is more likely to be wealthy than a country with a small and unproductive workforce. Productivity can be improved through education, training, and technology.</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#institutions","title":"Institutions","text":"<p>The rules and regulations that govern a country's economy can also play a role in its wealth. Good institutions, such as a strong legal system and a fair tax system, can help to promote economic growth.</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#other-factors","title":"Other factors","text":"<ul> <li>Entrepreneurship</li> <li>Innovation</li> <li>Trade</li> </ul>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#smiths-observations","title":"Smith's Observations","text":"<ul> <li>Adam Smith argued that people want more than just the basic necessities of life.</li> <li>They also want things that make life easier, more convenient, and more entertaining.</li> <li>The more of these things people have, the richer they are, at least in economic terms.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#what-is-economics-all-about","title":"What is Economics All About?","text":"<ul> <li>Economics is about understanding the choices that people and businesses make.</li> <li>It is about how these choices affect the distribution of resources and the overall well-being of society.</li> <li>Economics is also about understanding the forces that drive economic growth and development.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#economic-enigmas","title":"Economic Enigmas","text":"<ul> <li>Economists study economic enigmas, or puzzles and riddles that can be explained through economic analysis.</li> <li>For example, why does popcorn sold at the movies cost more than at a grocery store?</li> <li>Or why are so many products sold for $2.99 and so few for $3.00?</li> </ul>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#economics","title":"Economics","text":"<ul> <li>The study of how people use their limited resources to satisfy their unlimited wants.</li> <li>Resources are anything used to produce an economic good or a service.</li> <li>Wants are what people desire, but not all wants can be satisfied.</li> <li>Scarcity is the condition in which there are not enough resources to satisfy all wants.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#microeconomics","title":"Microeconomics","text":"<p>The study of economic decision making by individuals, households, and businesses. Focuses on how these individual units interact with each other and with the market. Macroeconomics</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#macroeconomics","title":"Macroeconomics","text":"<p>The study of the workings of an economy as a whole. Focuses on topics such as economic growth, inflation, and unemployment.</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#the-science-of-decision-making","title":"The Science of Decision-Making","text":"<ul> <li>Economics is also the study of how people make choices.</li> <li>When people cannot have everything they want, they must make choices about how to allocate their resources.</li> <li>Economists study how people make these choices and how they are affected by the choices of others.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#seven-economical-principles","title":"Seven Economical Principles","text":""},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#scarcity-forces-tradeoffs","title":"Scarcity Forces Tradeoffs","text":"<p>People have unlimited wants but limited resources, so they must make choices.</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#cost-benefit-principle","title":"Cost-Benefit Principle","text":"<p>People make choices based on the expected costs and benefits.</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#thinking-at-the-margin","title":"Thinking at the Margin","text":"<p>Most decisions involve choices about a little more or a little less of something.</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#incentives-matter","title":"Incentives Matter","text":"<p>People respond to incentives in generally predictable ways.</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#trade-makes-people-better-off","title":"Trade Makes People Better Off","text":"<p>By focusing on what we do well and then trading with others, we can all get more of what we want.</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#markets-coordinate-trade","title":"Markets Coordinate Trade","text":"<p>Markets are usually the best way to coordinate exchanges between buyers and sellers.</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#future-consequences-count","title":"Future Consequences Count","text":"<p>People take into account the future consequences of their choices.</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#the-scientific-method","title":"The Scientific Method","text":"<p>Economists use the scientific method to study how the economy works.</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#questioning-and-hypothesizing","title":"Questioning and Hypothesizing","text":"<p>Economists start by asking a question about how the economy works.</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#conducting-studies-and-collecting-information","title":"Conducting Studies and Collecting Information","text":"<p>To test their hypothesis, economists conduct studies and collect information.</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#analyzing-the-information","title":"Analyzing the Information","text":"<p>Once economists have collected the information, they analyze it to see if it supports their hypothesis.</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#evaluating-the-hypothesis","title":"Evaluating the Hypothesis","text":"<p>Finally, economists evaluate their hypothesis and decide whether it is supported by the evidence.</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#economic-models","title":"Economic Models","text":"<p>A simplified representation of reality that often allows economists to focus on the effects of one change at a time. Models also help economists structure their thinking.</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#types-of-economic-models","title":"Types of Economic Models","text":"<p>Mathematical models, computer models, diagrammatic models, and verbal models</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-1.html#limitations","title":"Limitations","text":"<ul> <li>Models are an approximation of how people, in general, act. As such, models cannot accurately predict all behavior all of the time.</li> <li>Economists who construct models must make assumptions. These assumptions can limit the applicability of the model.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html","title":"Chapter 2: Factors of Production","text":""},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#the-five-steps-of-economic-decision-making","title":"The Five Steps of Economic Decision-Making","text":"<ol> <li>Define the problem. What is the decision that needs to be made?</li> <li>Identify possible alternatives. What are the different options available?</li> <li>Develop criteria and a ranking system. How will the alternatives be evaluated?</li> <li>Evaluate alternatives against the criteria. Which alternative is the best?</li> <li>Make a decision. Implement the chosen alternative.</li> </ol>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#economic-fundamentals","title":"Economic Fundamentals","text":"<ul> <li>Our wants always exceed our resources. We desire many things, but we can only afford to have a limited number of them.</li> <li>The choices we make are influenced by our wants and our resources. We have to decide what we want most and what we are willing to give up to get it.</li> <li>The choices we make can have a big impact on our lives. The decisions we make about our education, our careers, and our relationships can all affect our happiness and success.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#scarcity","title":"Scarcity","text":""},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#types-of-scarcity","title":"Types of Scarcity","text":"<ul> <li>Absolute scarcity means that there is not enough of a resource to meet everyone's needs.</li> <li>For example, there is not enough water for everyone in the world to have enough to drink.</li> <li>Relative scarcity means that there is not enough of a resource to meet everyone's wants.</li> <li>For example, there is not enough money for everyone in the world to have a private jet.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#the-causes-of-scarcity","title":"The Causes of Scarcity","text":"<p>There are three main causes of scarcity:</p> <ul> <li>Limited resources: There are only a finite number of resources in the world.</li> <li>Unlimited wants: We have unlimited wants for goods and services.</li> <li>Different wants: People have different wants, and these wants often conflict with each other.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#the-consequences-of-scarcity","title":"The Consequences of Scarcity","text":"<ul> <li>Scarcity forces us to make choices.</li> <li>We have to decide which of our wants are most important and which ones we can afford to give up.</li> <li>Scarcity also leads to competition.</li> <li>People compete for resources, and this can lead to conflict.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#human-capital","title":"Human Capital","text":"<p>Human capital is the skills and knowledge that people have that can be used to produce goods and services.</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#importance-of-human-capital","title":"Importance of Human Capital","text":"<ul> <li>Human capital is important for economic growth.</li> <li>A more skilled workforce can produce more goods and services.</li> <li>Human capital can also help to reduce poverty.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#ways-to-increase-human-capital","title":"Ways to Increase Human Capital","text":"<ul> <li>Education: Education is the most important way to increase human capital.</li> <li>Training: Training can help people to develop new skills and knowledge.</li> <li>Experience: Experience can also help people to develop skills and knowledge.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#capital","title":"Capital","text":"<ul> <li>Capital is the tools, machines, and buildings used in the production of other goods and services.</li> <li>It can take a surprising number of forms, from simple screwdrivers to complex supercomputers.</li> <li>Capital has replaced labor in many industries, but it has also created new jobs in the design, production, and maintenance of new machines.</li> </ul>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#financial-capital","title":"Financial Capital","text":"<p>Money used in the production of goods &amp; services</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#physical-capital","title":"Physical Capital","text":"<p>Goods and services used in the production of other goods &amp; services</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#entrepreneurship","title":"Entrepreneurship","text":"<p>Ability to combine land, labor, and capital in new ways to produce goods &amp; services</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#types-of-entrepreneurship","title":"Types of Entrepreneurship","text":""},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#innovator","title":"Innovator","text":"<p>Thinks of ways to use new inventions, technologies, or techniques to into goods &amp; services</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#strategist","title":"Strategist","text":"<p>Supplies vision and key decisions to set direction for new businesses</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#risk-taker","title":"Risk-Taker","text":"<p>Not afraid to put in the time, effort, and resources not knowing if they will succeed</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#sparkplug","title":"Sparkplug","text":"<p>Supplies the energy, determination, and enthusiasm needed to turn ideas into reality</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#productivity","title":"Productivity","text":""},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#production-equation","title":"Production Equation","text":"<pre><code>graph TD\n    G[Goods and Services]\n    Land --&gt; G\n    Labor --&gt; G\n    Capital --&gt; G\n    Entrepreneurship --&gt; G</code></pre> <p>Producitivty Ratio $$ \\frac{\\text{Output}}{\\text{Input}} $$</p> <p>How can we increase productivity?</p> <ul> <li>Increase the amount of resources</li> <li>Increase the amount of output</li> <li>Increase the amount of output per unit of input</li> </ul>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#choices","title":"Choices","text":""},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#utility","title":"Utility","text":"<p>Satisfaction one gains from the consumption of a good or service</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#marginal-utility","title":"Marginal Utility","text":"<p>Satisfaction from the consumption of one or more unit</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#law-of-diminished-marginal-utility","title":"Law of Diminished Marginal Utility","text":"<p>As you consume more units of any good or service, the additional satisfaction from each additional unit will eventually start to decrease</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#opportunity-cost","title":"Opportunity Cost","text":"<p>Value of the next best alternative you could have chosen</p> <p>Knowing the cost or value of your choices can help you make a decision now</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#production-possibility-frontier","title":"Production Possibility Frontier","text":"<p>An economic model that shows (at the moment) all combinations of how an economy might use its reousrces to produce two goods</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#economic-efficiency","title":"Economic Efficiency","text":"<p>Using resources to produce the maximum amount of goods and services</p>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#production-possibility-curve","title":"Production Possibility Curve","text":"<p>Represents the maximum amount of goods and services that can be produced using a fixed amount of resources</p> <ul> <li>Any point along the curve that meets the needed demand is allocative efficient</li> <li>Any point along the curve that minimizes costs is productive efficient</li> <li>Anything inside the curve is economically inefficient</li> <li>Anything outside the curve is unattainable </li> </ul>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-2.html#shifters-of-the-ppc","title":"Shifters of the PPC","text":"<ul> <li>Change in the quantity of resources</li> <li>Change in the quality of resources</li> <li>Change in technology</li> <li>Change in trade</li> </ul>"},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-3.html","title":"Chapter 3","text":""},{"location":"economics/notes/chapter-3.html#introduction","title":"Introduction","text":"<p>Economic decision making is the process of choosing among alternative courses of action in order to achieve a desired outcome. It is a complex process that is influenced by a variety of factors, such as individual preferences, prices, and income.</p>"},{"location":"senior-bible/wijws/3-4.html","title":"What if Jesus Was Serious Pt. 1: 3, 4","text":""},{"location":"senior-bible/wijws/3-4.html#prompt","title":"Prompt","text":"<p>Read #3 &amp; #4 (24-25; 26-27 &amp; additional Bible passages) and answer the following questions.</p> <ol> <li>How has your own understanding of heaven influenced how you think about the \"Kingdom of God?\"</li> <li>Respond to Dallas Willard's definition of kingdom of heaven. How does that change how we think about our role within the KOH? </li> <li>Define lament in your own terms. How can we strike a balance of celebration between the \"good news\" of Jesus and grieving the world</li> </ol>"},{"location":"senior-bible/wijws/3-4.html#response","title":"Response","text":"<ol> <li> <p>I do not believe in heaven, however, I can understand how these concepts can be meaningful to people who do believe in them. The kingdom of God can be seen as a metaphor for a world where there is peace, love, and justice. It can be a source of hope and inspiration for people who are struggling in the world.</p> </li> <li> <p>Dallas Willard's definition of the kingdom of heaven is kind of interesting. I agree with him that it is not a place, but a way of life. However, there are some aspects to which I would disagree with, the core reasoning being that our perspective on religion, specifically Christianity, is different.</p> </li> <li> <p>I define lament as a way of expressing grief and sorrow. It is a way of acknowledging the pain and suffering in the world, and of asking for help to make things right. I think that lament is an important part of the human experience, regardless of whether you believe in God.</p> <p>I believe that we can strike a balance between celebration and lament by being honest with ourselves. We can celebrate the good things that happen, while also acknowledging the pain and suffering. Most importantly, it's alright to say that we don't know the answer to something too.</p> </li> </ol>"},{"location":"senior-bible/wijws/intro-1-2.html","title":"What if Jesus Was Serious Pt. 1: Intro, 1 &amp; 2","text":""},{"location":"senior-bible/wijws/intro-1-2.html#prompt","title":"Prompt","text":"<p>Read Intro (pp. 9-12) Part One: Who is Really Blessed? Matthew 5.1-12 Then read #1 &amp; #2 (16-18, 20-22 including 1 Samuel 16.7; Luke 13.22-30, James 2.1-9; 1 Cor. 1.26-31) and answer the following questions.</p> <ol> <li>How does Jesus challenge our understanding of blessing? </li> <li>In what ways has our collective misunderstanding of the Beatitudes led to a failed witness? </li> <li>How can Social Media be reclaimed to communicate the ways that Jesus discusses blessing? </li> <li>How does Paul reinforce Jesus\u2019 message on blessing in 1 Corinthians 1.26-31?</li> </ol>"},{"location":"senior-bible/wijws/intro-1-2.html#response","title":"Response","text":"<ol> <li>Jesus challenges our understanding of blessing by redefining what it means to be blessed. He says that the poor in spirit are blessed, the meek are blessed, and those who mourn are blessed. These aren\u2019t the people that the world considers to be blessed, but the world values wealth, power, and status. Jesus says that those who are poor in spirit, meek, and mourning are the ones who are truly blessed.</li> <li>Leading us to focus on material blessings rather than spiritual blessings  as well as neglect the poor and marginalized. The Beatitudes call us to bless those who are poor, hungry, and imprisoned. However, we often turn a blind eye to these people. We see them as a burden or a threat, rather than as people who are blessed by God.</li> <li>We can use social media to share stories of people who are living out the Beatitudes, advocate for the poor and marginalized and to challenge the culture of judgment and self-righteousness.</li> <li>He points out that God chose the foolish, weak, and lowly things of the world to shame the wise, strong, and powerful. This shows that God's definition of blessing is different from the world's definition, rather than material possessions or status. Its supposed to be about things like humility, meekness, and love.</li> </ol>"}]}